{{Infobox video game | title = EA Sports Active NFL Training Camp | collapsible = | state = | image = EA Sports Active NFL Training Camp box.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = The box art of ''EA Sports Active NFL Training Camp'' | developer = [[EA Canada]] | publisher = [[EA Sports]] | series = | engine = | platforms = [[Wii]] | released = {{vgrelease|NA|November 16, 2010}} | genre = [[Exergaming|Fitness]] | modes = }} '''''EA Sports Active [[Training camp (National Football League)|NFL Training Camp]]''''' is an [[American football]]-based [[exergaming|fitness]] video game developed by [[EA Canada]] and published by [[EA Sports]] for the [[Nintendo]] [[Wii]]. The game was released on the same day as ''[[EA Sports Active 2]]''. The game has the [[National Football League]] license, which allows players to work out with any team and player of their choice, and was developed with the collaboration of various NFL strength and conditioning coaches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/ea/nfltrainingcamp?module=HP_spotlight |title=EA Sports NFL Training Camp |publisher=NFL.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref> The game is compatible with the [[Wii Balance Board]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Mojo |url=http://www.nflshop.com/product/index.jsp?productId=10860090 |title=EA Sports Active NFL Training Camp Video Game for Wii |publisher=NFLShop.com |date=2011-11-28 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref> Unlike the [[EA Sports Active|past]] [[EA Sports Active 2|two]] games, ''NFL Training Camp'' has "Total Body Tracking", which uses a heart monitor to measure the player's heart rate during play, along with a wireless motion tracker<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investor.ea.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=530677 |title=Touchdown! EA SPORTS Active NFL Training Camp Launches Today (NASDAQ:EA) |publisher=Investor.ea.com |date=2010-11-16 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref> which goes on the leg, while the heart rate monitor goes on the arm, unlike the other games, which makes use of a leg pouch and the [[Wii Remote#Nunchuck|Nunchuck]].<ref name=GameSpot>{{cite web|author=July 20, 2010 7:57PM PDT |url=http://www.gamespot.com/ea-sports-active-nfl-training-camp/previews/ea-sports-active-nfl-training-camp-first-impressions-6270411/ |title=EA Sports Active NFL Training Camp First Impressions |publisher=GameSpot.com |date=2010-11-16 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref> The game's online compatibility is used by plugging a [[USB flash drive]] into the back of the console, and progress that the player makes in the game is automatically recorded and posted on the player's online profile.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiifitnessdepot.com/wii-fitness/ea-sports-active-nfl-training-camp/ |title=EA Sports NFL Training Camp: Get Fit Like Real NFL Players |publisher=Wiifitnessdepot.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref> EA discontinued the game's online service on April 13, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://games.ign.com/articles/122/1221117p1.html |title=EA Shutting Down Several Game Servers - Xbox 360 News at IGN |publisher=Games.ign.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref>
==Gameplay== In ''NFL Training Camp'', players perform various drills that are commonly performed in the [[NFL Scouting Combine]], such as the [[40-yard dash]]. At the end of every drill, a graph appears to inform the player of how many calories he/she has burned throughout the course of the drill, as well as the median of the player's heart rate. Players are rewarded with points and achievements for their performance.<ref name=GameSpot /> In the game, the player can participate in the ''NFL Combine 60-Day Challenge'', which lets players work for four days per week for 60 days in the [http://www.nfl.com/combine/workouts drills] performed in the Combine.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stack |first=Kyle |url=https://www.wired.com/playbook/2010/11/total-body-tracking/ |title=EA Brings NFL Training Camp Into Your Home &#124; Playbook |publisher=Wired.com |date=2010-11-18 |accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref> Points and achievements that are earned by the player can be compared to other people who have played on the console, as well as people on the player's friend list. The game also has set up public groups for players to join, and players can contribute their stats to their team.<ref name=GameSpot />
==Reception== {{Video game reviews | GSpot = 8.2/10 | rev1 = Operation Sports | rev1Score = 7.5/10 }} Operation Sports gave the game a 7.5/10, praising the drills, workouts, and equipment, but criticized the feedback and motion problems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.operationsports.com/reviews/581/ea-sports-active-nfl-training-camp/ |title=EA Sports Active NFL Training Camp Review (Wii) |publisher=Operation Sports |date= |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref>
