{{for|the Vice-Chancellor of Oxford University|George William Hall}} {{Infobox baseball biography |name=George Hall |position=[[Outfielder]] |image=George Hall 1874.jpg |bats=Left |throws=Left |birth_date={{birth date|1849|3|29}} |birth_place=[[Stepney, England]] |death_date={{death date and age|1923|6|11|1849|3|29}} |death_place=[[Ridgewood, Queens|Ridgewood, New York]] |debutleague = MLB |debutdate=May 5 |debutyear=1871 |debutteam=Washington Olympics |finalleague = MLB |finaldate=October 6 |finalyear=1877 |finalteam=Louisville Grays |statleague = MLB |stat1label=[[Batting average]] |stat1value=.322 |stat2label=[[Home run]]s |stat2value=13 |stat3label=[[Runs batted in]] |stat3value=252 |teams= ;&nbsp; [[National Association of Base Ball Players]] : Enterprise of Brooklyn (1866) : [[Excelsior of Brooklyn]] (1867) : Star of Brooklyn (1868&ndash;1869) : [[Brooklyn Atlantics]] (1870) ;&nbsp; [[National Association of Professional Base Ball Players|National Association]] : [[Washington Olympics]] (1871) : [[Baltimore Canaries]] (1872–1873) : [[History of the Atlanta Braves#Boston years|Boston Red Stockings]] (1874) : [[Athletic of Philadelphia]] (1875) ;&nbsp; [[National League]] : Athletic of Philadelphia (1876) : [[Louisville Grays]] (1877) |highlights= * [[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders|NL home run leader]] (1876) }} '''George William Hall''' (March 29, 1849 &ndash; June 11, 1923) was a professional [[baseball]] player who played in the [[National Association of Professional Baseball Players|National Association]] and later the [[National League]]. Born in [[Stepney]], England, Hall later immigrated to the U.S. He made his professional debut on May 5, 1871.<ref name="retrosheet">{{cite web| title = George Hall's statistics | work = retrosheet.org | url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/H/Phallg101.htm | accessdate = 2007-12-18 }}</ref>
==Early career==
Hall began his professional career with the [[Washington Olympics]] of the National Association in {{Baseball year|1871}}, [[batting average|hitting]] .294 in 32 games. He moved onto the [[Baltimore Canaries]] for the {{Baseball year|1872}} and {{Baseball year|1873}} seasons, hitting .336 and .345 respectively.<ref name="retrosheet"/> Playing mostly [[Center fielder|center field]] up to this point, he moved around from center to [[right field]] the following year when he played for the {{Baseball year|1874}} Champions, the [[History of the Atlanta Braves#Boston years|Boston Red Stockings]].<ref name="retrosheet"/><ref name="1874standings">{{cite web| title = 1874 National Association Standings | work = retrosheet.org | url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1874/Y_1874.htm | accessdate = 2007-12-18 }}</ref> After just one season with the Red Stockings, he moved on to play for the [[Philadelphia Athletics (1860–76)|Philadelphia Athletics]] where he had another good season at the plate, hitting .299, and four [[home run]]s, which was good for second place behind [[Jim O'Rourke (baseball)|Jim O'Rourke]]'s six.<ref name="1875leaders">{{cite web | title = 1875 National Association Leaders | work = baseball-reference.com | url = https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NA_1875_t.shtml | accessdate = 2007-12-23 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071215012651/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NA_1875_t.shtml | archivedate = 2007-12-15 | df = }}</ref>
==National League== [[File:George hall.jpg|thumb|200px|left]] After the 1875 season, the National Association folded, which left room for a new league to begin. In {{Baseball year|1876}}, the [[National League]] came into existence, the first official "Major League". Hall's team, the Athletics, followed that movement with very little success, finishing seventh out of eight teams.<ref name="1876standings">{{cite web | title = 1876 National League Standings | work = baseball-reference.com | url = https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL_1876.shtml | accessdate = 2007-12-23 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071212103916/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL_1876.shtml | archivedate = 2007-12-12 | df = }}</ref> One of the bright spots that year for the Athletics was the hitting prowess of their star hitter, Hall. He led the team in almost all major hitting categories including a .366 batting average, 51 [[run (baseball)|runs scored]], and a league leading five home runs.<ref name="retrosheet"/> On June 17, 1876, he became the first Major League baseball player to hit two home runs in one game.<ref name="chronology">{{cite web|title=George Hall Chronology |work=baseballlibrary.com |url=http://www.baseballlibrary.com/ballplayers/player.php?name=George_Hall_1849&page=chronology |accessdate=2007-12-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604120120/http://www.baseballlibrary.com/ballplayers/player.php?name=George_Hall_1849&page=chronology |archivedate=June 4, 2011 }}</ref> Those five home runs stood as the single season home run record until [[Charley Jones]] hit nine in {{Baseball year|1879}}.
For the {{Baseball year|1877}} baseball season, Philadelphia had been expelled from the league for refusing to go on a western road trip, late in the 1876 season, for financial reasons, so Hall moved on to play for the [[Louisville Grays]]. Again, he had an excellent season, hitting .323, scoring 51 runs, and hitting 8 [[triple (baseball)|triples]]. Surprisingly, after appearing in the league leaders for home runs the last two seasons, he did not hit one in 1877.<ref name="retrosheet"/>
===Possible first cycle=== Some baseball researchers attribute Hall as being the first major league player to [[hitting for the cycle|hit for the cycle]].<ref name=huber>{{cite web |url=http://sabr.org/gamesproj/game/june-14-1876-george-hall-gets-five-hits-it-cycle |title=June 14, 1876: George Hall gets five hits, but is it a cycle? |first=Mike |last=Huber |website=[[Society for American Baseball Research|SABR]] |accessdate=November 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.retrosheet.org/cycles_chron.htm |title=Cycles Chronologically |website=[[Retrosheet]] |accessdate=November 20, 2017}}</ref> In a game against the [[Cincinnati Reds (1876–80)|Cincinnati Red Stockings]] on June 14, 1876, Hall had five hits.<ref name=huber/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18457466/base_ball/ |title=Base Ball |newspaper=[[The Boston Post]] |page=2 |date=June 15, 1876 |accessdate=March 20, 2018 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref> Contemporary newspaper accounts agree that four of the hits were a home run, a single, and two triples; there is disagreement as to if the remaining hit was a double (which would complete the cycle) or another triple.<ref name=huber/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18457510/cincinnati_vs_athletic/ |title=Cincinnati vs. Athletic |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |page=5 |date=June 15, 1876 |accessdate=March 20, 2018 |via=newspapers.com |quote="Hall made a home run and three three-base hits."}}</ref> The first undisputed major league cycle is attributed to [[Curry Foley]] of the [[Buffalo Bisons (NL)|Buffalo Bisons]] of the National League in 1882.<ref name=huber/>
==Gambling scandal and banishment== On October 26, 1877, Louisville club vice president Charles Chase confronted Hall and fellow Gray [[Jim Devlin]] with charges that they threw some road games in August and September. Both admitted only to throwing non-league games, one of which was an exhibition game in [[Lowell, Massachusetts]], on August 30, and another in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], on September 3. The admissions also implicated teammates [[Al Nichols]] and [[Bill Craver]]. Hall claimed that he and Devlin helped in losses to the [[Cincinnati Reds]] on September 6 and to the [[Minor League Baseball|minor league]] [[Indianapolis Blues]] on September 24‚ but he argued that since the Reds were about to be suspended and the games nullified‚ it amounted to an exhibition game.<ref name="chronology"/> As a result of the [[1877 Louisville Grays scandal|scandal]], all four players were [[List of people banned from Major League Baseball|banned for life from Major League Baseball]].
Hall died in [[Ridgewood, Queens|Ridgewood, New York]], at the age of 74. He was buried at [[Cemetery of the Evergreens, Brooklyn|Evergreen Cemetery]] in [[Brooklyn, New York]].<ref name="retrosheet"/>
