{{Infobox football club | clubname = Sport Club Cañadense | image = Sport club canadense.png | image_size = 100px | fullname = Sport Club Cañadense | nickname = ''Celeste'' | founded = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1913|8|5}} | ground = | capacity = | chairman = Guillermo Conejo | manager = | league = Liga Cañadense de Fútbol | season = [[2011-12 in Argentine football|2011–12]] | position = | website = http://www.sportcc.com.ar/ |pattern_la1=|pattern_b1=_thin_dark_grey_hoops|pattern_ra1=|leftarm1=77CBF0|body1=77CBF0|rightarm1=77CBF0|shorts1=000000|socks1=77CBF0 |pattern_la2=|pattern_b2=_thin_dark_grey_hoops|pattern_ra2=|leftarm2=000000|body2=000000|rightarm2=000000|shorts2=000000|socks2=000000 | }}
'''Sport Club Cañadense''' is an [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[sports club]] from [[Cañada de Gómez]], [[Santa Fe Province]]. Although many sports are practised at the club, the institution is mostly known for both its [[association football|football]] and [[basketball]] teams.
The club's football team plays in the Liga Cañadense de Fútbol, a local tournament which Sport Club won 18 times, becoming the top title-winner in league history.<ref>[http://www.sportcc.com.ar/paginas.php?id_pagina=23 Información sobre el equipo de fútbol mayor de Sport Club]</ref> The basketball squad plays at the [[Torneo Nacional de Ascenso]] (TNA), the second division of the [[Liga Nacional de Básquetbol]], which Sport Club participated 11 seasons. The team's most important achievement was in 1990, when reached the final games against [[Atenas de Córdoba]] but Sport Club finally was defeated 0–3.
Other sports hosted by Cañadense are [[field hockey]], [[gymnastics]], [[roller skating]], [[swimming (sport)|swimming]] and [[tennis]].
